# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] A presidential election was held in South Carolina on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1789 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose 7 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina, which became the 8th state on May 23, 1788, unanimously cast its seven electoral votes for George Washington during its first presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] A presidential election was held in South Carolina between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose eight members of the Electoral College, each of whom, under the provisions of the Constitution prior to the passage of the Twelfth Amendment, cast two votes for President.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina's eight electors each cast one vote for the incumbent, George Washington; with one exception, each of those electors cast a second vote for Vice President John Adams, the outlier voting for Aaron Burr.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The Federalist Party dominated South Carolina in the 1790s as it could count a number of prominent lowcountry planters among their ranks.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Many South Carolinians played important roles for the Federalist Party at the national level.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The Jeffersonian-Republicans, however, were rising in prominence, especially as Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and Pierce Butler, both of whom signed the Constitution for South Carolina, joined the rival party.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Although the Federalists dominated the state until 1800, by 1804 there were no Federalists in power.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina would remain a one-party state until the start of the Civil War.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1793-united-states-senate-election-in-south-carolina] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1808 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place between November 4 and December 7, 1808, as part of the 1808 United States presidential election.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose 10 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1808-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] During this election, South Carolina cast its 10 electoral votes to Democratic Republican candidate and Secretary of State James Madison.
